Face Mask Prediction using U-Net¶

Task is to predict the mask around the face in a given image.

Instructions¶

  • Some part of the code is already done for you
  • You need to execute all the cells
  • You need to add the code where ever you see "#### Add your code here ####"
  • Marks are mentioned along with the cells

Dataset¶

Faces in images marked with bounding boxes. Have around 409 images with around 1000 faces manually tagged via bounding box.

  • Data file name: images.npy

Set image dimensions (1 mark)¶

  • Initialize image height, image width with value: 224
In [7]:
IMAGE_HEIGHT = 224
IMAGE_WIDTH = 224

Create features and labels¶

  • Here feature is the image
  • The label is the mask
  • Images will be stored in "X" array
  • Masks will be stored in "masks" array
In [8]:
import cv2
from tensorflow.keras.applications.mobilenet import preprocess_input

# Have removed pre-processing from here and kept it in ImageDataGenerator 
masks = np.zeros((int(data.shape[0]), IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH),dtype=np.uint8)
X = np.zeros((int(data.shape[0]), IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3),dtype=np.uint8)
for index in range(data.shape[0]):
    img = data[index][0]
    img = cv2.resize(img, dsize=(IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH), interpolation=cv2.INTER_CUBIC)
    try:
      img = img[:, :, :3]
    except:
      continue
    X[index] = img
    for i in data[index][1]:
        x1 = int(i["points"][0]['x'] * IMAGE_WIDTH)
        x2 = int(i["points"][1]['x'] * IMAGE_WIDTH)
        y1 = int(i["points"][0]['y'] * IMAGE_HEIGHT)
        y2 = int(i["points"][1]['y'] * IMAGE_HEIGHT)
        masks[index][y1:y2, x1:x2] = 1

Split the data into training and testing (2 marks)¶

  • 400 images in training
  • 9 images in testing data

Data split

In [9]:
# Instead of keeping all 400 in training data, have split full set into train, validation and test dataset
X_train, X_val, X_test = X[0:370,:,:,:], X[370:400,:,:,:], X[400:,:,:,:]

# Reshaping the mask data because Img data generator accepts in below format
y_train, y_val, y_test = masks[0:370,:,:].reshape(370,224,224,1), masks[370:400,:,:].reshape(30,224,224,1), masks[400:,:,:].reshape(9,224,224,1)

from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
In [188]:
# Image date generator setup
image_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rotation_range=15, width_shift_range=0.15, height_shift_range=0.15,shear_range=0.15, zoom_range=0.2, fill_mode='nearest', horizontal_flip=True,preprocessing_function=preprocess_input, dtype=np.float64)
mask_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rotation_range=15, width_shift_range=0.15, height_shift_range=0.15,shear_range=0.15, zoom_range=0.2,  fill_mode='nearest', horizontal_flip=True, dtype=np.uint8)
seed = 1
image_datagen.fit(X_train, augment=True, seed=seed)
mask_datagen.fit(y_train, augment=True, seed=seed)

image_generator = image_datagen.flow(X_train,seed=seed,batch_size=1)
mask_generator = mask_datagen.flow(y_train,seed=seed,batch_size=1)

# combine generators into one which yields image and masks
train_generator = zip(image_generator, mask_generator)

# Validation set
#preprocessing_function=preprocess_input,
image_datagen_val = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess_input,dtype=np.float64)
mask_datagen_val = ImageDataGenerator(dtype=np.uint8)
seed = 1
image_datagen_val.fit(X_val, augment=True, seed=seed)
mask_datagen_val.fit(y_val, augment=True, seed=seed)

image_generator_val = image_datagen_val.flow(X_val,batch_size=1,seed=seed)
mask_generator_val = mask_datagen_val.flow(y_val,batch_size=1,seed=seed)

# combine generators into one which yields image and masks
val_generator = zip(image_generator_val, mask_generator_val)

Create the model (5 marks)¶

  • Add MobileNet as model with below parameter values
    • input_shape: IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3
    • include_top: False
    • alpha: 1.0
    • weights: "imagenet"
  • Add UNET architecture layers
    • This is the trickiest part of the project, you need to research and implement it correctly
In [96]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications.mobilenet import MobileNet
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Reshape, UpSampling2D, Concatenate, Conv2D,Conv2DTranspose,BatchNormalization,Dropout,SeparableConv2D,SpatialDropout2D
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model

def create_model(full_model_train=False,conc_trainable=False):
    model = MobileNet(input_shape=(IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3), include_top=False, alpha=1.0, weights="imagenet")

    conv_con_list=['conv_pw_1_relu','conv_pw_3_relu','conv_pw_5_relu','conv_pw_8_relu','conv_pw_11_relu','conv_pw_12_relu','conv_pw_13_relu']

    for layer in model.layers:
      if conc_trainable and layer in conv_con_list:
        layer.trainable = conc_trainable
      elif full_model_train:
        layer.trainable = full_model_train
      else:
        layer.trainable = False
  
    conv1 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_1_relu").output
    conv3 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_3_relu").output
    conv5 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_5_relu").output
    conv8 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_8_relu").output
    conv11 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_11_relu").output
    conv12 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_12_relu").output
    conv13 = model.get_layer("conv_pw_13_relu").output
    
    deconv1_con= Concatenate()([conv13, conv12])
    deconv1_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(deconv1_con)
    deconv1_dout= SpatialDropout2D(0.3)(deconv1_bn)

    deconv2 = Conv2DTranspose(filters = 1024, kernel_size= (3, 3), padding='same', strides=(2,2), activation='relu')(deconv1_dout)
    deconv2_con= Concatenate()([deconv2, conv11, conv8])
    deconv2_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(deconv2_con)
    deconv2_dout= SpatialDropout2D(0.3)(deconv2_bn)

    conv2_1= Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size= (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(deconv2_dout)
    conv2_1_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(conv2_1)

    conv2_2= SeparableConv2D(filters=512, kernel_size= (3, 3),dilation_rate=(2, 2), depth_multiplier=1, activation="relu", padding="same")(conv2_1_bn)
    conv2_2_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(conv2_2)

    deconv3 = Conv2DTranspose(filters = 512, kernel_size= (3, 3), strides=(2,2),  padding="same", activation='relu')(conv2_2_bn)
    deconv3_con= Concatenate()([deconv3, conv5])
    deconv3_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(deconv3_con)
    deconv3_dout= SpatialDropout2D(0.3)(deconv3_bn)
    
    conv3_1= Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size= (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(deconv3_dout)
    conv3_1_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(conv3_1)

    conv3_2= SeparableConv2D(filters=256, kernel_size= (3, 3),dilation_rate=(2, 2), depth_multiplier=1, activation="relu", padding="same")(conv3_1_bn)
    conv3_2_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(conv3_2)

    deconv4= Conv2DTranspose(filters = 256, kernel_size= (3, 3), strides=(2,2),  padding="same", activation='relu')(conv3_2_bn)
    deconv4_con= Concatenate()([deconv4, conv3])
    deconv4_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(deconv4_con)
    deconv4_dout= SpatialDropout2D(0.3)(deconv4_bn)
    
    conv4_1= Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size= (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(deconv4_dout)
    conv4_1_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(conv4_1)

    conv4_2= SeparableConv2D(filters=128, kernel_size= (3, 3),dilation_rate=(2, 2), depth_multiplier=1, activation="relu", padding="same")(conv4_1_bn)
    conv4_2_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(conv4_2)

    deconv5= Conv2DTranspose(filters = 128, kernel_size= (3, 3), strides=(2,2), padding="same", activation='relu')(conv4_2_bn)
    deconv5_con= Concatenate()([deconv5, conv1])
    deconv5_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(deconv5_con)
    deconv5_dout= SpatialDropout2D(0.3)(deconv5_bn)
    
    conv5_1= Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size= (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(deconv5_dout)
    conv5_1_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(conv5_1)

    conv5_2= SeparableConv2D(filters=64, kernel_size= (3, 3),dilation_rate=(2, 2), depth_multiplier=1, activation="relu", padding="same")(conv5_1_bn)
    conv5_2_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(conv5_2)

    deconv6= Conv2DTranspose(filters = 64, kernel_size= (3, 3),  strides=(2,2),  padding="same", activation='relu')(conv5_2_bn)
    deconv6_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(deconv6)
    
    conv6_1= Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size= (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(deconv6_bn)
    conv6_1_bn= BatchNormalization(axis=-1, momentum=0.99)(conv6_1)
    conv6_1_dout= Dropout(0.2)(conv6_1_bn)

    output_layer = Conv2D(filters=1, kernel_size= (3, 3), activation='sigmoid', padding='same')(conv6_1_dout)

    return Model(inputs=model.input, outputs=output_layer)

Call the create_model function (1 mark)¶

  • Give trainable=False as argument, if you want to freeze lower layers for fast training (but low accuracy)
In [97]:
model=create_model(full_model_train=True,conc_trainable=False)

Define dice coefficient function (2 marks)¶

  • Create a function to calculate dice coefficient
In [99]:
from tensorflow import reduce_sum
from tensorflow.keras.backend import epsilon
In [100]:
def dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred):
    numerator = 2 * reduce_sum(y_true * y_pred)
    denominator = reduce_sum(y_true + y_pred)

    return numerator / (denominator + epsilon())

Define loss function (2 marks)¶

In [101]:
from tensorflow.keras.metrics import binary_crossentropy
from tensorflow.keras.backend import log
In [102]:
def loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return binary_crossentropy(y_true, y_pred) - log(dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred) + epsilon())

Compile the model (2 marks)¶

  • Complie the model using below parameters
    • loss: use the loss function defined above
    • optimizers: use Adam optimizer
    • metrics: use dice_coefficient function defined above
In [103]:
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
In [104]:
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001,beta_1=0.9), loss=loss, metrics=[dice_coefficient], run_eagerly=None)

# patient early stopping and setting restore_best_weights=True allows to get back the model with best weights even with patience attribute setting

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', verbose=1, patience=30, restore_best_weights=True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', factor=0.3, patience=8, min_lr=1e-6, verbose=1)

Conclusion:¶

  1. Project is done using MobileNet model by applying Transfer learning.
  2. U-Net Architecture is built on top of mobilenet.
  3. Applied ImageDataGenerator as we have less training data.
  4. Performance of the model on test data seems to be satisfactory. However it can be further improved by having more training data.
